usjrforward: #OnTheGo

Jaguars overtake Wildcats in final Cesafi 23 Basketball elims

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars defeated the Cebu Institute of Technology-University (CIT-U) Wildcats, 77-63, in their final Cesafi 23 Men’s Basketball elimination match at the Cebu Coliseum on Sunday, November 26.

With over 5 minutes left on the game clock, USJ-R Jaguars’ Samuel Melicor earned the first score for the team as both were off to a slow opening quarter, 13-8.

The CIT-U Wildcats attempted a recovery with a point margin, 14-13, but Team Captain Jules Langres, Karl Malone Ventura, and Christian Sollano capitalized on their opponents’ weakening defense, ending the first half at 38-26.

Ventura, who chipped in 19 points for the team, poured in a series of treys in the third period which concluded with a 12-point gap (60-52).

Although they came alive during the final quarter by trimming the Jaguars’ point advantage to five, the Wildcats produced 11 points in their losing efforts.

Langres scored a total of 16 points and 17 rebounds, highlighted by two triples, as the Jaguars gained their seventh victory of the season. Milo Janao also contributed 11 points and 17 rebounds for the team.

Jaguars’ Head Coach Melo Banua commented on the team’s performance against the Wildcats.

“Gi-execute lang namo among gi-practice so far, pero na-down ang lamang by five [points]. Naa gihapo’y complacency,” Banua said.

Despite the Jaguars’ series of victories, the team’s spot in the semifinals is at stake as Cesafi officials investigate the eligibility of their player Evan Jose Agbong, particularly regarding his submitted records.

If Agbong’s records are deemed ineligible, the team’s chances of making it to the semifinals might be affected as appropriate sanctions determined by Cesafi will be imposed.

Cesafi officials have yet to announce their decision on Agbong and USJ-R’s status in the league.

Moreover, Banua shared that the Jaguars will keep on their practices regardless of the final decision.

“So far okay man among season [standing]. If tagaan mi og chance moduwa sa semis, we will prepare. Di gihapon mi moundang until next year. If tagaan mi og chance, maningkamot lang gyod mi,” he said.

Before the semifinals on December 5 and 7, the chosen Cesafi 23 players from the different member schools will participate in the All-Star Games to be held on Sunday, December 3, at the same venue.

The members of the All-Star Games’ teams are yet to be determined.

via Rey Martin Rio | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Christian Mananguite | FORWARD Staff Photographer

text:
usjrforward: #OnTheGo

Josenian grad clinches 5th spot in CELE 2023

Josenian alumna Analiza Mabini secured the fifth spot in the November 2023 Civil Engineers Licensure Examination (CELE) with a rating of 91.50% held on November 17-18, 2023.

Out of 18,582 examinees, the Professional Regulation Commission (PRC) officially declared that only 6,180 takers, or 33.26% successfully passed the licensure exam for civil engineers.

Mabini, a summa cum laude graduate of the Bachelor of Science in Civil Engineering program with a specialization in Structural Engineering, expressed that becoming a topnotcher was beyond her expectations and considers it a “miracle.”

“Truth be told, the exam was very hard for me. I even cried during the first night of our board exam,” she said.

Mabini shared that her whole review journey was the most challenging part, noting the need to study every day.

“Ang study kay would really take a toll on you, but you just believe in yourself jod. Never stop,” she stated.

Meanwhile, Mabini shared her way of lifting the exhaustion she felt on her journey.

“Mag-scroll na lang jod ko sa Facebook usahay if kapoy na jod kaayo, makigstorya ko sa akong ate kung unsa among mga kaagi pag childhood,” she said.

Mabini added that the time she spent talking with her friends was what she considered the “silver lining” during her review period, which she described as her “dark time.”

Mabini also parted advice to engineering students and aspiring engineers who are preparing for the licensure exam.

“Absorb everything that you will learn in the classroom because it would really help you in your review days…Study hard, aim high, [and] believe in yourself because there would be many times that you would doubt yourself,” she said.

During the press conference held at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) yesterday, November 25, the Dean of the School of Engineering, Dr. Dennis Kilongkilong, stated that the last time USJ-R had a topnotcher in the field of civil engineering was in 2019.

“We produced 22 new civil engineers for the School of Engineering in USJ-R and this is not a one-man show. It is a collaborative effort [between] the team Civil Engineering Department and the faculty and staff,” Kilongkilong said.

According to the USJ-R Vice President for Academics & Research, Rev. Fr. Jose Alden Alipin, OAR, Mabini will receive P75,000 and a brand new laptop as a reward.

via Trixcy Clar | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Ejay Villaver | FORWARD Staff Writer

text:
usjrforward: #OnTheGo

JBEES conducts acquaintance party ‘23

The University of San Jose-Recoletos Junior Business Executives and Entrepreneurs Society (USJ-R JBEES) hosted an acquaintance party with the theme, ”Golden Allure: An Evening of White and Gold Enchantment” at the Sugbutel Family Hotel on Saturday evening, November 25.

The event aimed to foster camaraderie and future collaborations among students under the degree programs of the Bachelor of Science in Business Administration major in Operations Management (BSBA OM) and Bachelor of Science in Entrepreneurship (BSE).

Despite facing obstacles, JBEES Vice President-External Lyndon Orcullo shared that he is satisfied with the successful execution of the long-awaited event.

Orcullo further stressed out the experience by saying that it is ”hard yet fulfilling.”

The program featured a runway showcasing members of the organization in their white and gold outfits, followed by a communal dinner.

Subsequently, engaging games served as ice-breakers for the guests, along with an intermission number by JBEESians under the class of Professor Francisco Gatdula serenading the crowd with their rendition of Christmas songs.

Meanwhile, JBEES President, Jehallel Enriquez, expressed his gratefulness for the success of the acquaintance party and was delighted with its conclusion.

Enriquez emphasized that the event is just the start of building connections between the students in the long run.

”We do hope that we’re gonna see more connections even with the students in the future events,” he added.

The event hailed Ethan Paul Pablo and Maxene Joson, the King and Queen of the Night, respectively.

via Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Khen Fernandez | FORWARD Probationary Artist

text:
usjrforward: #OnTheGo

USJ-R Jaguars sweep FRV Blue Spikers in Cesafi Vball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars blanked the Felipe R. Verallo (FRV) College Blue Spikers, 3-0, in the Cesafi 23 Men’s Volleyball game at the University of Southern Philippines (USPF) Gymnasium on Saturday, November 25.

The USJ-R Jaguars earned the match’s opening point and proceeded to seize the sets in their favor with scores of 25-7, 25-11, and 25-14.

The Jaguars were hot from the get-go as they overwhelmed the FRV College Blue Spikers, widening the point gap to 25-7.

The Blue Spikers tried to regain their footing during the second set, evident in their blocks, but eventually succumbed to the Jaguars’ attacks, 25-11.

With unfaltering momentum, the Jaguars ultimately secured the victory, thanks to Abrham Mahumot’s remarkable gameplay.

“One game at a time lang,” he said.

Mahumot expressed his hope for the team’s unity and teamwork to persist as they prepare to face their upcoming opponents.

“Nag-double time mi sa practice and nag-focus mi sa game and balance sa among time,” he added.

The Jaguars remain undefeated at 5-0 and aim to sustain this against the University of San Carlos (USC) Warriors at their home court on Monday morning, November 27.

via Ava Donalie Ferolino | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Heron Augustus Flores | FORWARD Probationary Artist

text:
usjrforward: #OnTheGo

Jaguars dominate football field against Fighting Maroons, 4-0

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars triumphed against the University of the Philippines-Cebu (UPC) Fighting Maroons, 4-0, in the Cesafi 23 Football game at the University of San Carlos (USC) Talamban Campus on Saturday, November 25.

In the first half, the Jaguars demonstrated strong offense with Dustin Ramirez and Jay Cupas making notable attempts, while Loie Jay Opsima capitalized on the 20th-minute mark to earn the first goal.

The team also showcased a good defensive performance as Enzo Urot and MC Maiko Silva added to the action.

Forward player Silva secured the second goal, while Team Captain and Goalkeeper Eugene De Arce denied the UPC Fighting Maroons any scoring opportunities.

Meanwhile, the second half unfolded with close attempts from Robert Jumapit and Dodge De Arce, with De Arce finding the net but was nullified due to an offside violation.

A foul by Jan Michael Oliveros led to a penalty shot for the Fighting Maroons, but the Jaguars prevailed as they successfully guarded it.

During the closing minutes of the match, the Fighting Maroons unintentionally scored an own goal, further extending the Jaguars’ lead.

Kirk Dustin Alabate sealed the Jaguars’ victory with the last goal, securing the team’s third win of the season.

Jaguars’ Head Coach Joselito Bono commented on the team’s victory.

“We focused more on the buildup kaya [naka-]score, score, score,” Bono said.

“There were also a lot of goal attempts gikan sa UP sad, but I am very happy with the players’ performance,” he added.

The USJ-R Jaguars will face the University of Cebu (UC) Webmasters in their last match for the elimination rounds later today, November 26, at 3 p.m. and at the same venue.

via Maria Cristina Lamug | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Hannah Vanessa Mondilla | FORWARD Staff Artist

text:
usjrforward: #OnTheGo

USJ-R recognizes 62 employees for their years in service

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) hosted the 2023 Service Awards with the theme "Celebrating Josenian Service and Excellence Under the Starry Sky," to acknowledge the unwavering dedication of 62 employees for their years of service to the institution, at the Radisson Blu Hotel, Cebu City on November 23.

The event honored 12 retirees, two 35-year employees, seven 30-year employees, nine 25-year employees, seven 20-year employees, 12 15-year employees, and 13 10-year employees, all of whom received recognition for their exemplary contributions to the Josenian community and University throughout the years.

During the event, Teodoro Cagang, one of the retirees, expressed his gratitude on behalf of other retirees in serving the institution by saying they were “inflamed by the fire of Recoletos’ charisma.”

“For all that we have achieved in life, from the start of our journey in USJ-R until today, be it physical, psychological, spiritual, or educational, we can only thank God that we are planted by this beloved institution...This is the moment that I will always look back with dignity and pride as long as I live, and to be able to thank the institution that molded me,” he expressed.

In a separate interview with FORWARD, 35-year service awardee, Perlita Long, shared her sentiments and reasons for staying as a Junior High School (JHS) faculty member at the University.

“I’m so grateful, kay more than half of my life is with USJ-R starting when I was in elementary till college. There were many opportunities for me to leave this institution, but the feeling of love in USJ-R remains in my heart and it will always be in my heart,” she shared.

Moreover, Rev. Fr. Hernando Coja, OAR, the longest-serving religious administrator of USJ-R and the first Filipino President of the then-Colegio de San Jose-Recoletos (now known as USJ-R), expressed his appreciation for the awardees and staff who have kept their “enthusiasm and passion in nurturing the students.”

“My advice for the new ones is to at least adopt the environment and cooperate to work hand-in-hand in order to uplift San Jose...For the old ones, I would like to thank them for what they have done, and to keep on,” he shared.

The awarding ceremony concluded with a message from Rev. Fr. Leopoldo Estioko, OAR to the Josenian community to continue their “zealous commitment and passion,” like how Jesus left an example to His disciples in loving and serving others.

via Khabzeel Clark Payao | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Krista Marie Yaoyao | FORWARD Probationary Artist

“I’m so grateful, kay more than half of my life is with USJ-R starting when I was in elementary till college. There were many opportunities for me to leave this institution, but the feeling of love in USJ-R remains in my heart and it will always be in my heart,” she shared.

Moreover, Rev. Fr. Hernando Coja, OAR, the longest-serving religious administrator of USJ-R and the first Filipino President of the then-Colegio de San Jose-Recoletos (now known as USJ-R), expressed his appreciation for the awardees and staff who have kept their “enthusiasm and passion in nurturing the students.”

“My advice for the new ones is to at least adopt the environment and cooperate to work hand-in-hand in order to uplift San Jose...For the old ones, I would like to thank them for what they have done, and to keep on,” he shared.

The awarding ceremony concluded with a message from Rev. Fr. Leopoldo Estioko, OAR to the Josenian community to continue their “zealous commitment and passion,” like how Jesus left an example to His disciples in loving and serving others.

via Khabzeel Clark Payao | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Krista Marie Yaoyao | FORWARD Probationary Artist

text:
usjr.official: #JosenianPride | IT student Alexis Parales is set to leave the country this week and be one of the students to represent the Philippines in an international tech competition in Indonesia.

During the national tilt, her team won 2nd runner-up. Alexis also got the Performance Excellence Award for being one of the top scorers in the whole competition.

HackForGov aims to increase the pace of developing cyber-proficient students and engage them to take a path in cybersecurity to increase the pool of cyber-proficient individuals, develop problem-solving skills required to identify, and mitigate cybersecurity attacks by providing real-world examples thru the analysis of challenges.

usjr.official: The feast day of Nuestra Señora de la Salud was celebrated today at the Recoletos Eco-Pilgrimage Park in Danao City.

Josenians and residents of Barangay Maslog attended a holy mass and shared a meal together. The celebration was originally scheduled last Friday but it was deferred due to heavy rains.

This is the first and only eco-park of the Order of the Augustinian Recollect (OAR). It was inaugurated in 2015.
